<br>
Reactor rockets were first seriously experimented with in the US during the mid 50's under the Project name of ROVER and culminating in NERVA. It was built and tested to prove the concept of nuclear powered space flight and was a total success. Other programs leading up to it included `Kiwi`, `Peewee`, and `Nuclear Furnace`which all explored the basics of nuclear rocket reactor technology. Each new reactor rocket demonstrated increasingly greater specific impulses, power levels and power densities. The Rover Program was cancelled in 1972 after the U.S abandoned plans to send men to Mars.  <br>
NERVA demonstrated double the thrust of today's best chemical rockets and would have required a fraction of the fuel mass to reach orbit. Single stage launches would have been possible and how much further efficiency might have been gained is unknown.<br>
