<br>
You apparently have nuclear thermal propulsion confused with ion<br>
propulsion... <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> big difference</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Nuclear thermal propulsion is very simply a nuclear reactor used to<br>
super heat a propellant (hydrogen) to provide thrust.  A test system<br>
was built in the 1960's... called NERVA.  Tests indicate that a NTR<br>
would provide 2 to 3 times the specific impulse of conventional<br>
chemical rockets.<br>
<br>
Please read the following, and make note of the transit times (the<br>
fastest at &gt;100 km/sec), also note that this is a 'Miniature Thermal<br>
Rocket':<br>
<br>
=======================================================================<br>
The MITEE (MIniature Thermal ReacTor EnginE) is a compact nuclear thermal propulsion engine based on<br>
tungsten - UO2 composite fuel developed in the 1960's for the 710 nuclear propulsion program. Depending on the<br>
MITEE reactor configuration and operating parameters, specific impulse in the range of 900 to 1200 seconds is<br>
possible. Engine mass is in the range of 100 to 200 kilograms, depending on the type of nuclear fuel used. MITEE<br>
designs utilizing U-235, U-233, and Am-242m fuels are described.<br>
New and unique missions are enabled by MITEE, including flyby of Pluto with a 5-year trip time, a Pluto<br>
orbiter/lander to observe the predicted atmospheric condensation in 2020, a Europa lander/sample return with a 5<br>
year round trip time, and a fast probe (&gt;100 km/sec) to near interstellar space including the Kuiper Belt, Heliopause,<br>
and the Gravitational Lensing Point, based on a V burn close to the Sun. <br>
A development program for the MITEE engine is outlined to achieve initial mission capability by 2008. Since the<br>
MITEE reactor is based on an assembly of individual pressure-tube fuel elements, much of the development can be<br>
carried our using tests on a single pressuretube/ fuel element, initially with non-nuclear electric heating, followed by<br>
confirmatory nuclear heating tests.<br>
