b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The fact is that Nuclear thermal rockets ARE a form of ion rockets - but a LESS efficient form.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Complete and utter bullshit.  Ion engines accelerate charged Ions out the back where NTR exhaust is not charged.  NTRs also don't need electricity to operate.  As for your baseless assertion that NTRs don't have enough thrust they come pretty close to a T/W of 1 and could provide high acceleration.  I suggest you do a little reading up on them.  If your book says they are ion engines then your book should be thrown out.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The specific impulse of nuclear thermal rockets varies from 500 - 1100 seconds for solid core versions however such systems are very difficult to control due to the intense heating of the reactor core.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
NTRs are actually quite easy to control.  You just need to control the fuel flow and reactivity which can be done with valves and control drums.<br>
